That&#x27;s how it feels, but the syntax for declaring multiple variables breaks it:<p><pre><code>    int* a, b;
</code></pre>
is equivalent to<p><pre><code>    int *a;
    int b;
</code></pre>
not<p><pre><code>    int *a;
    int *b;
</code></pre>
So while I think it makes sense to think of the pointer nature as part of the type I stopped using it as the risk of writing incorrect code was too great.<p>Though there&#x27;s also the option of forbidding shorthand declaration. Then you can write<p><pre><code>    int* a;
    int* b;
</code></pre>
especially if you have a linter letting you add such a syntax rule.
